properties.column_1: Widely Used Classification Schemes for US Office Markets
*Categorizing US (Office) markets is not an exact science
We have summarized some of the prevelant schemes above:
- "Gateway cities" are those favored by institutional investors, domestic andeven mor though international investors
- Gateway cities overlap nicely with 24-hour cities (L.A. is not a 24-hour city)
- RCAnalytics has its own classification scheme (Primary, Secondary, Tertiary)
- "There is a "Widely Accepted" classification of First, Second, and Third Tier markets. There usually are 10 or 11 in the First Tier segment. (Is Denver or Miami in or not?)

- Will GLL only invest in the Gateway Cities? No, we prefer them and do want to be invested in these markets for the long term. However, we will make investments in select other markets as long as the deals and the terms warrant such investment.
- Share of Transaction market shows the market share" of each market (a) among only US investors, and (b) among only non-US Investors
Population ranking values are from 2010 US Census city-data.com
